reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on February 4, 2024
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Nice USB for what I needed it for
reviews.reviewText: I didn't need this for anything fancy, but when I saw it had USBC capabilities as well I was sold. It was much more solid than I was expecting, which was a nice plus, and I like that it has the loop to connect it to my keys so I don't have to worry about losing it. Definitely a good choice!

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on January 18, 2024
reviews.reviewTitle: 4.0 out of 5 stars Nice design, adequate speed.
reviews.reviewText: TLDR:If you think it looks cool or want a double ended USB drive and are super concerned with read / write speeds go for it. If you plan to copy to and from frequently and in large amounts, move alone.The good:This drive has a solid feel to it, it has some weight, it feels good in your hand. Being able to use either USBC or USBA is a bonus. They way it rotates, it almost like a fidget spinner for adults. From that point of view, I love it.The bad:This is sold and marketed as a USB 3 drive. As someone who understands USB 2, 3, and variations, allow me to explain. USB 3.0 (also known USB 3.2 Gen 1 because USB's naming convention is horrible) is capable of speeds of 5.0Gbps. Now you'll nowhere get those speeds on a USB 3 flash drive, those are the max throughput. USB 2.0 is capable of 480MbpsHere's the thing, the MAX write speed I could get is 30 MB, and pretty much about the same for reading. I expect better from a USB flash drive. 30MBps = 240Mbps. Meaning the speed is still in USB 2.0 territory. This test was done on two systems, a Z590 using a 3.2 Gen 2 port, and an LG Gram 1260p USB 4.0 port. My computer is not bottlenecking the system.So after testing it out and being disappointed I can back and looked at their listing more closely. One of their images states USB 3 (20-40 Read 15-30 Write).So yeah for the price, it's current price, it's acceptable. Nothing to write home about. Won't be using as my primary.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on February 1, 2024
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Perfect fit for my keychain thumb drive
reviews.reviewText: I have a Dell XPS laptop that only has USB C ports, but I need to use USB A for a lot of programming tasks and sneakernet items. i have a thumb drive from sandisk that was like this, but it was made of plastic and the USB A port has a lot of chipped off plastic bits. the USB C side is still in tact, but it free spins. this drive has 4 clickable positions on it so it stays where you put it. the metal body is really nice. 5/5, would recommend.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on January 21, 2024
reviews.reviewTitle: 2.0 out of 5 stars 64GB capacity, USB C and A (but it can't fully be closed), SLOW Speeds - NOT USB-C 3.1
reviews.reviewText: I see this item is no longer available so I can't comment on the price, but I suspect they had to remove it as the packaging says USB 3.1. After running speed tests, this drive runs at 40 MB/s read and 34 MB/s write which is lower than the average speed for USB 3, and is DEFINITELY not USB 3.1 as written on the box. Those speeds are more in line with USB 2.0. Other than that having both USB A and USB C options is nice, but you can't fully close it.Regardless, this item isn't even available anymore so a 2/5 from me seems reasonable.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on January 20, 2024
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Don't need a Mac dongle with this one!
reviews.reviewText: I love the fact that this can switch between a Type-C and USB3.0 !! I was so happy when I found this since I can easily switch between devices that will have either one or the other. It works perfectly. The only tiny negative is that one end remains exposed in your bag when the other end is covered, so just have to be careful not to damage the exposed end in transport.
